<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920221-0119</DOCNO><DOCID>920221-0119.</DOCID><HL>   CenTrust Ex-Official   Is Ordered to Prison   For Civil Contempt</HL><DATE>02/21/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   DLP</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>FLORIDA (FL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   MIAMI -- David L. Paul, former chairman of CenTrustSavings Bank, was ordered yesterday to serve as much as 18months in prison after being found in civil contempt ofcourt.   U.S. District Judge Stanley Marcus said Mr. Paul showed&quot;knowing and willful disobedience&quot; in failing to comply withthree court orders to produce documents related to CenTrustfor a grand jury investigation of the failed thrift. In hisorder, the judge denied a motion by Mr. Paul for bail andordered him to begin serving his sentence Monday.</LP><TEXT>   CenTrust, which had invested heavily in junk bonds throughDrexel Burnham Lambert, was shut down by federal regulatorsin 1990. Its failure could cost taxpayers $2 billion.   Mr. Paul's attorney, Aubrey Harwell of Nashville, Tenn.,said he immediately filed an appeal of Judge Marcus's orderwith the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals for a ruling onwhether the orders to surrender the documents pose aviolation to Mr. Paul's Fifth Amendment right againstself-incrimination. In addition, Mr. Harwell said that thefederal authorities who closed CenTrust have copies of thedocuments at issue. &quot;There are other sources that governmentprosecutors could get those records-namely, other governmentagencies,&quot; he said.</TEXT></DOC>